<br>
Also, you point out some of the more extreme cases in our country and yet will not take the same yourself. I won't go into a diatribe about France here, but I will point out a few things that you seem to be ignorant of here.<br>
<br>
As for the coffe incident, it was an 87 year old woman who was riding in a car with her son. She put the coffee between her legs and her son hit the gas a little too hard and that is how it spilled. The coffee also comes in thick styrofoam cups so it is entirely possible she did nbot realize how hot it was.<br>
<br>
As for the death penalty. It takes on average 10 years, with an average of 13 oppurtunities for the death sentence to be overridden, before someone is put to death. The only weay they are put to death is if there is a proponderence of evidence against them that persists for many years. Also the ones who are put to death ar ethe really mean ones, a single murder usually just nets you life. You have to almost be in the double digits before your death penalty material, generally.<br>
<br>
Our coffee may be weak by your standards, but that is hardly a basis for attack. Its not like I can't go get dark coffe if that is what I prefer, it is however not what is generally served.<br>
<br>
You should also keep in mind that America is a classless society, for the most part. There is a certain seperation between rich and poor to be sure, but it is probably mroe slight than you think. I myself came from a very poor family and grew up in a rough part of town. Sharn is from a similiar situation, although not as extreme. That has proven to be no impediment to us at all. The office I work in currently, out of 13 people, has 4 self made millionaires. Keep in mind, they are self made, they also came from nothing. The big boss so to speak never went past the 8th grade and came from a very poor family, however with time and hard work he became a succesful businessman and a millionaire many times over. In many countries, I not coming from a family with money, would not be expected to be on an equal level with such people. However, in America I am and no one acts like the money is an issue. I didn't even know that the four were millionaires until about a month after I had started working there.<br>
<br>
Another thing to consider is that Americans are indeed proud of their country and what our forefathers achieved in our country. Not a one of em were saints for sure, but they did accomplish something remarkable in a historically spekaing short amount of time. We are proud of that, I see no problem with a little deserved pride.<br>
<br>
Also on the school issue, I lived in one of the poorest parts of a poor town, and the school system there was not a very good one. So I simply attended a neighboring school system that had more of the programs I was looking for in school. Even though I was pretty sharp I opted for the vocational route instead of the college route, purely my own choice to do so, and I have never regretted it. I have seen every style of school in this country, private, public, and home school. I have also seen a variety of job types, factory work, telemarketing, sales, entertainment, office, and blue collar. I speak from experience and an understanding of how things really work in America when I speak, I don't think you'll find anyone to disagree. <br>
<br>
Our system is not perfect by a long shot, but then again no system ever is. We certainly have our problems, as you have yours. And just like yourself we seek to fix these problems and improve the system, and we need time to do it in and will make mistakes, just as any other country. Just like you we have outspoken idiots and wonderous members of the human race. Don't be so quick to judge, as that is a true sign of the very ignorence and arrogence you yourself seem to be irritated by so much. My mother had a saying which ahs always proven golden to me. &quot;Those who scream loudest about something are usually its worst offenders.&quot; Perhaps you should harken to her words and not be so quick to make snap judgements and condemm something you understand no more than I understand most French issues.<br>
<br>
 <p>&quot;For a day I had my dream. And on that day, it was my duty to end that dream.&quot;<br>
